The points \( z_1 \), \( z_2 \), \( \frac{1}{z_1} \), and \( \frac{1}{z_2} \) form a convex quadrilateral. To find the area of this quadrilateral, we use the shoelace formula. The coordinates of the vertices are: - \( z_1 = (a, b) \) - \( z_2 = (a, -b) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_2} = \left( \frac{a}{10}, -\frac{b}{10} \right) \) - \( \frac{1}{z_1} = \left( \frac{a}{10}, \frac{b}{10} \right) \) Using the shoelace formula, the area is calculated as: \[ \text{Area} = \frac{1}{2} \left| -99ab \right| = \frac{99ab}{100} \] To maximize this area, we need to maximize \( ab \) under the constraint \( a^2 + b^2 = 10 \).
